<validation>
1. Successfully inject instructions that modify LLM behavior
2. Extract system prompt or internal instructions
3. Bypass content filters to generate restricted content
4. Exfiltrate sensitive data from context or training
5. Manipulate RAG to return poisoned documents
6. Abuse agent tools to perform unauthorized actions
7. Demonstrate cost exhaustion or rate limit bypass
8. Provide reproducible prompts showing each attack
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Models with robust instruction-following safeguards
- Strong prompt injection filters
- Proper input sanitization for RAG documents
- Agent tools with least-privilege access
- Rate limiting and cost controls enforced
- PII scrubbing from context and training data
- Multi-layer validation of model outputs
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Arbitrary code execution via agent tool abuse
- Data exfiltration (PII, API keys, credentials)
- Content policy bypass (malicious content generation)
- Cost exploitation (API bill inflation)
- RAG poisoning (misinformation injection)
- Authorization bypass (privileged action execution)
- Privacy violations (training data extraction)
- System prompt disclosure (architecture information)
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Test both direct input and indirect sources (documents, emails, web pages)
2. Start with simple injections, escalate to complex multi-step attacks
3. RAG systems are often vulnerable to document poisoning
4. Agent tools are high-value targets—map all available functions
5. Test with multiple phrasings—models vary in robustness
6. Context window overflow can bypass system prompts
7. Combine techniques: image + text, multi-language, encoding
8. Monitor model responses for metadata leakage
9. Test cost-based attacks separately (high impact, easy to detect)
10. Save working prompts—model updates may patch specific patterns
11. Jailbreaks often work better with roleplay/hypothetical framing
12. Tool calling often has weaker validation than direct prompts
13. Test memory systems for injection across sessions
14. Multi-modal inputs (images with embedded text) are less filtered
15. Document extraction attempts carefully—high sensitivity
</pro_tips>

<remember>LLM security is fundamentally different from traditional application security. Prompt injection is the new code injection. There's no perfect defense—only layers of mitigation. RAG systems amplify attack surface through document poisoning. Agents with tools create confused deputy scenarios. Every input to an LLM is potentially adversarial. Test both technical exploitation and social engineering of the model. The boundary between legitimate use and attack is often unclear. Focus on demonstrating impact while respecting scope and ethics.</remember>
</llm_integration_security_guide>
